This is horrible. Black is going to have a huge lead in development and is much better now.

e4 is perhaps inaccurate. Not only because the pawn can be easily liquidated (which isn't too big of a problem as black is so far ahead that the open lines may help), but because after 7 ... Nc6! black gets to develop naturally with ... Nf6 and it isn't too clear how white is going to survive black's lead in development.
This actually doesn't lose much time, since the queen was going to be attacked by Nf6 anyway.
Perhaps instead Qh5! and Qd1!, but it isn't clear that white can hold anyway.

Nbc2?? is a positional blunder of titanic proportions. Instead after Nd3! white's position is in ruins: The Nd3 is almost impossible to remove in the short term, and it prevents the development of the d2 pawn and c1 bishop. It also focuses on the white king. Just as an example, after ... Qh4 black is already forced into Nh3 to guard f2, and then g5-g4 wins the knight. Very likely many other aggressive maneuvers win by a similarly absurd magnitude.
Of course, black appears to remain winning.
